  "doc_id": "31371",
  "text": "A very reasonable voting function which is often used in elections is the majority rule. In this voting function, for each pair of outcomes, the order between them in the result is what the majority says on this pair. This function, however, can produce an ordering which is cyclic and thus it is not a social welfare function. A sufficient condition on profiles that avoids generating cycles is the triple-wise value-restriction [CITATION_1] : for every triple of outcomes x 1 , x 2 , x 3 , there exists x i ∈ {x 1 , x 2 , x 3 } and r ∈ {1, 2, 3} such that no agent ranks x i as his r-th preference among x1, x2, x3.",
